 Our baseline model was a Linear Regression model predicting avg_rating using 9 recipe-level features: minutes, n_steps, n_ingredients, calories, sugar, protein, carbohydrates, total_fat, and sodium. All 9 of these features were quantitative, with 0 ordinal and 0 nominal features. Because they were all numeric, we did not need to use one-hot encoding or ordinal encoding. We handled missing values with median imputation and standardized the features before fitting the model. We used this model as a simple baseline so that we could compare it with more advanced models later.
Our final model was a CatBoostRegressor predicting smoothed_rating rather than raw avg_rating. We used smoothed_rating because recipes with only a small number of ratings can have unstable averages, so smoothing makes the target more reliable by shrinking recipes with few ratings toward the overall mean. The final model used 21 total features, and all 21 were quantitative, with 0 ordinal and 0 nominal features. These included recipe and nutrition features (minutes, n_steps, n_ingredients, calories, sugar, protein, carbohydrates, total_fat, sodium), engineered features (calories_per_ingredient, n_ratings), aggregated review-model features (rev_pred_mean, rev_pred_std, rev_pred_min, rev_pred_max, rev_count), and aggregated sentiment/text features (sent_mean, sent_std, sent_pos_mean, sent_neg_mean, review_length_mean). Since the final feature set was entirely numeric, we again did not need any categorical encoding, and missing values were handled with median imputation.
To bring in information from the text reviews, we used TF-IDF in an intermediate step rather than directly in the final CatBoost model. We first transformed review text into TF-IDF features using unigrams and bigrams, then trained a Ridge regression model to predict review ratings from the text. After that, we aggregated those predicted review scores to the recipe level, which gave us features such as the mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum predicted review score for each recipe. We also included aggregated sentiment and review-length features. These features make sense for the prediction task because ratings are not only influenced by the recipe itself, but also by how people describe their experience with it. For example, more positive reviews, more consistent review scores, and stronger sentiment patterns should all relate to higher recipe ratings. Recipe-level features such as time, ingredients, and nutrition also matter because they reflect recipe complexity and the type of food being made.
We chose CatBoost because it can model nonlinear relationships and interactions better than a simple linear model. That is useful here because recipe ratings probably do not depend on things like calories, cooking time, and number of ingredients in a perfectly linear way. The best CatBoost settings were iterations = 4000, learning_rate = 0.03, depth = 6, loss_function = "RMSE", and random_seed = 42, with the final version selected using a validation set and use_best_model=True. For the text stage, we used TF-IDF with max_features = 80000, ngram_range = (1,2), and min_df = 2, along with Ridge regression using alpha = 50.0. We selected the final model by comparing it with the baseline and other candidate models on held-out performance.
In terms of results, the baseline Linear Regression had MAE = 0.4652, RMSE = 0.641, and R² = 0.00016. The final CatBoost model had MAE = 0.0267, RMSE = 0.0380, and R² = 0.5496. This is a large improvement over the baseline. The final model makes much smaller errors and explains a much larger share of the variation in ratings, while the baseline explains almost none. Because of that, we believe the final model is good, especially compared to the baseline. It is clearly capturing useful information from both the structured recipe features and the review-based features. At the same time, it is not perfect, since an R² of about 0.55 still means there is some variation in ratings that the model cannot explain, which makes sense because user ratings are subjective and noisy.
